<div class="clear-block">

<div class="who">

  
  <a href="/users/james-johnson" title="View user profile.">James Johnson</a></div> <!-- /.who -->

<div class="what">
    <span class="submitted">
    08/30/11 at 6:23 pm  </span>
  <span class="editcomment"> 
    </span>
  <p class="content"><p>Do these supposed environmental benefits include the production of potassium hydroxide by electrolysis of potassium  chloride? or the inefficiencies of transporting the KOH solution via truck-tanker vs existing natural gas pipelines for traditional cremation?<br />
Isn't this very similar to the manufacture of soap via the saponification reaction with sodium hydroxide? So the sewered wastewater would be no worse than a soap manufacturer's wastewater (assuming complete reaction of KOH or post-neautralization with HCL).<br />
I find if interesting that most people will have a difficult time accepting the sewering of human remains, however, "Bones remain and are pulverized to ash in the usual way" will have no effect on them.<br />
All cultures and societies have varying funeral rights and ceremonies. While this may seem odd to us now, in 20 years it will be commonly accepted.</p>
</p>
  </div> <!-- /.what -->

</div>


